en whose husbands lost their jobs, fell ill, drank up their wages, deserted their families, or died.Working Families explores the complex variety of responses of working-class families to their new lives within industrial capitalist society, and offers new ways of looking at the industrial revolution in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aFamilieszQuébec (Province)zMontréaly19th centuryvStatistics. 0aFamilieszQuébec (Province)zMontréaly19th century. 0aFamilieszQuébec (Province)zMontréaly19th centuryvStatistics. 0aFamilieszQuébec (Province)zMontréaly19th century. 0aWomenzQuébec (Province)zMontréalxHistoryy19th century. 0aWomenzQuébec (Province)zMontréalxHistoryy19th century. 0aWorking classzQuébec (Province)zMontréalxHistoryy19th century. 0aWorking classzQuébec (Province)zMontréalxHistoryy19th century. 4aCoursebook. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Post-Confederation (1867-).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066769108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781442685475423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442685475.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066769-1  UTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG